      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Selling a Tenanted Investment Property in Queensland: What Landlords Need to Know
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Selling with a tenant in place involves obligations that do not apply to a standard owner-occupier sale. Here is what Queensland landlords need to understand before they list.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Selling an investment property that has a tenant in place adds a layer of complexity that many landlords underestimate when they first decide to sell. The Residential Tenancies and Rooming Accommodation Act 2008 (RTRA Act) governs the relationship between landlord, tenant, and the sales process in Queensland, and its obligations do not pause simply because you have decided to sell. Understanding those obligations before you list will save you from disputes, delays, and potentially from a buyer walking away at the last minute.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Your obligations to the tenant during the sales campaign</h2>
      <p>Once you decide to sell, you are required to give your tenant reasonable notice before showing the property to prospective buyers. Under the RTRA Act, you must give the tenant at least 24 hours written notice for each entry to the property, and entry can only occur between 8am and 6pm on business days, or at a time agreed with the tenant. You cannot simply schedule open homes at your convenience and expect the tenant to accommodate them without proper notice.</p>

      <p>The tenant is also entitled to quiet enjoyment of the property throughout the campaign. That means you cannot run unlimited inspections per week simply because it suits your marketing strategy. The Act does not set a hard cap on the number of inspections, but a court would consider whether the frequency was unreasonable given the tenant's right to quiet enjoyment. In practice, this means working with your property manager and your agent to schedule open homes and private inspections at times that are mutually agreed with the tenant wherever possible.</p>

      <p>If you do not have a managing agent and are managing the tenancy directly, you will need to handle all of this communication in writing and keep records. It is a good idea to engage a property manager or solicitor to handle the tenant liaison if you are not familiar with the notice requirements.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What access rights does the buyer have before settlement?</h2>
      <p>Under the standard REIQ contract, the buyer is entitled to one pre-settlement inspection, typically in the 48 to 72 hours before settlement, to confirm the property is in the same condition as at the date of contract. This inspection is subject to the same notice requirements as any other entry, so the tenant must receive at least 24 hours written notice.</p>

      <p>Beyond the pre-settlement inspection, the buyer does not have a general right to access the property prior to settlement simply because they wish to measure rooms or plan renovations. Any additional access must be negotiated with the tenant through proper channels and agreed in writing. Buyers who push for multiple visits before settlement during a tenanted sale are sometimes surprised by this, and it is worth managing their expectations early in the campaign so it does not become a point of conflict.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Fixed-term leases that run past settlement</h2>
      <p>One of the most common complications in a tenanted investment sale arises when the property has a fixed-term lease that extends beyond the proposed settlement date. In Queensland, a fixed-term tenancy cannot be ended simply because the property has been sold. The buyer takes on the property subject to that tenancy, and the tenant has the right to remain until the fixed term expires under the same conditions.</p>

      <p>This matters significantly for who will buy the property. An investor buyer may be entirely comfortable purchasing with an existing tenancy in place, particularly if the rental income is at market rate and the tenant has a good payment history. An owner-occupier buyer, however, will almost certainly require vacant possession at settlement and will not be able to wait out a fixed-term lease that has months remaining. This effectively removes a large portion of the buyer pool from your campaign if you have a long-term fixed lease in place.</p>

      <p>The options available to you in this situation include waiting until the fixed term expires before listing, listing and accepting that you are targeting investor buyers only, or negotiating with the tenant for an early termination by mutual agreement under section 277 of the RTRA Act. Early termination requires the tenant to genuinely agree: you cannot pressure or incentivise them improperly. If an agreement can be reached, it must be documented formally.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Periodic tenancies and vacant possession</h2>
      <p>If the tenancy is periodic (a rolling month-to-month arrangement after a fixed term has ended), you have more flexibility. Under the RTRA Act, a landlord can end a periodic tenancy without grounds by giving the tenant at least four months written notice if the property is being sold. This means you could serve notice, allow the tenancy to end, and then list the property vacant once the notice period has elapsed.</p>

      <p>Alternatively, you can list while the periodic tenancy is in place, noting that buyers who require vacant possession would need the four-month notice period factored into the settlement timeline. This is less common for inner-east Brisbane sales, where settlement periods of 30 to 60 days are standard, but it can be structured contractually where a buyer is willing to wait.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Selling with a tenant vs selling vacant: the buyer pool question</h2>
      <p>The strategic question for most landlords is whether to sell with the tenant in place or arrange for the property to be vacant before listing. There is no universally correct answer: it depends on the nature of the tenancy, the rental income, the property type, and the likely composition of buyers in your suburb and price bracket.</p>

      <p>Selling with a tenant in place has real advantages when the rental income is strong and the tenant is reliable. Investor buyers can purchase knowing the yield from day one, without the holding cost risk of a vacant property. In suburbs where investor demand is active, this can be genuinely attractive. A property with a long-term, well-maintained tenancy and a history of on-time rent payments can be a positive selling point, not an obstacle.</p>

      <p>The downside is that owner-occupier buyers are largely excluded, and in Brisbane's inner east, owner-occupiers represent the largest and most competitive segment of the buyer pool. A property that would attract eight to twelve serious owner-occupier buyers at an auction may attract only three to five investor buyers when tenanted. The reduced competition almost always affects the price outcome.</p>

      <p>Properties that have been lived in by tenants also often present differently from owner-occupied homes. Personal belongings, the tenant's taste in furnishings, and the general wear of a rental can all make it harder for buyers to emotionally connect with the property. Styling and presentation options that would be available in a vacant home are simply not possible when someone is living there.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How rental income history affects value</h2>
      <p>For investor buyers, the rental history and current rental income are material facts that will influence their offer. A property that has been consistently tenanted at or above market rent, with no extended vacancy periods and a demonstrated history of well-maintained tenancies, supports a higher yield and therefore a stronger purchase price from a yield-focused buyer.</p>

      <p>If the current rent is below market, investor buyers will price in the time and cost of bringing it to market rate, which effectively discounts their offer. In Brisbane's inner east, where rents have moved considerably in recent years, properties that were set and left at their 2020 rental rates can look significantly underlet to an investor comparing them to current comparable leases. This is worth reviewing before you sell: if you have not increased rent to market rate and the tenancy permits it, doing so before going to market can meaningfully improve your outcome with investor buyers.</p>

